Name: Concurrent Map Access
Headline: A benchmark to compare the performance of different concurrent map access implementations in Go.
Description: The classic map access is done by using the `map[key]` syntax. This implementation works fine in the most cases, but it is not thread-safe. A solution is to use the `sync.Map` type or to add a mutex to the map. This benchmark shows which implementation is the fastest.

Benchmarks.Name: Mutex
Benchmarks.Description: Uses a `sync.RWMutex` to protect a plain `map[int]int`. Reads take a shared lock (`RLock`), writes take an exclusive lock (`Lock`). This is the standard approach when you control all access sites and need fine-grained locking with concurrent readers.

Benchmarks.Name: Sync
Benchmarks.Description: Uses the `sync.Map` type from the standard library. It is inherently thread-safe and needs no external locking. Optimised for keys that are stable over time â€” performs best when entries are written once and read many times.
